<P>This Stone is not intire, but hath the names of all the <GAP DESC="foreign">, tho&s;e Heroes from whom the <HI>Athenian</HI> Tribes had their names; and under the name of each Tribe, are &s;everal names of the <GAP DESC="foreign">, or Towns they con&s;i&s;ted of. La&s;t of all, a Li&s;t of many other names under the Title of &Egr;&Pgr;&Egr;&Ngr;&Ggr;&Rgr;&Agr;&PHgr;&Ogr;&Igr;, or &Egr;&Ngr;&Ggr;&Rgr;&Agr;&PHgr;&Ogr;&Igr;; which from <HI>Stephanus</HI> in the word <GAP DESC="foreign">, I believe refers to tho&s;e who were enrolled in the <HI>A|cropolis,</HI> <GAP DESC="foreign">. The learned Sir <HI>John Marskam,</HI> with other our Antiquaries, judge it belonged to a <HI>Gymna&s;ium;</HI> which will further appear, if compared with two other fragments, one of which I have, and the other I hope in a &s;hort time to recover from <HI>A|thens.</HI> That yet at <HI>Athens,</HI> &s;hews what kind of Title that of the Tribes had, being to this purpo&s;e, <HI>viz.</HI></P>
<P><HI>The Co&s;metes, or Supervizor of the Youth, Julius Zenon, and his Antico&s;metes, Ophyllius Ari&s;ton cau&s;ed tho&s;e under-written Go|vernours, and Youths, to be enrolled, when Philotimus. Son of Archi&s;idemos, was Archon.</HI></P>
