&Pgr;&Agr;&Igr;&OHgr;&Ngr; &Dgr;&Igr;&Ogr;&Mgr;&EEgr;&Dgr;&Ogr;&Ugr;&Sgr; &Pgr;&Agr;&Lgr;&Lgr;&EEgr;....<LB>
&Sgr;&Egr;&Xgr;&Sgr;&Tgr;&Igr;&Ogr;&Sgr; &Ngr;&Igr;&Kgr;&Agr;&Ngr;&OHgr;&Rgr; &Sgr;&PHgr;&EEgr;&Tgr;&Tgr;&Igr;&Ogr;....<LB>
&Pgr;&Igr;&Sgr;&Tgr;&Ogr;&Kgr;&Rgr;&Agr;&Tgr;&EEgr;&Sgr; &PHgr;&Igr;&Lgr;&Ogr;&Sgr;&Tgr;&Rgr;&Agr;&Tgr;&Ogr;&Ugr; &Agr;..<LB>
&Agr;&Bgr;&Agr;&Sgr;&Kgr;&Agr;&Ngr;&Tgr;&Ogr;&Sgr; &Egr;&Ugr;&Mgr;&Ogr;&Lgr;&Pgr;&Ogr;&Ugr; &Kgr;&EEgr;....<LB>
&Egr;&Rgr;&Mgr;&Igr;&Agr;&Sgr; &Tgr;&Rgr;&Ugr;&PHgr;&OHgr;&Ngr;&Ogr;&Sgr; &Mgr;&Agr;&Rgr;&Agr;&THgr;&OHgr;....<LB>
&Kgr;&Egr;&Sgr;&Tgr;&Rgr;&Ogr;&PHgr;&Ugr;&Lgr;&Agr;&Xgr; &Pgr;&Ugr;&THgr;&Igr;&Kgr;&Ogr;&Sgr; &Egr;&Ugr;&Dgr;&Ogr;...<LB>
&THgr;&Ugr;&Rgr;&OHgr;&Rgr;&Ogr;&Sgr; &Agr;&Igr;&Sgr;&KHgr;&Igr;&Ngr;&EEgr;&Sgr; &Ogr; &Kgr;&Agr;&Igr; &PSgr;&Igr;&Agr;..</Q>The third was a Pede&s;tal of a Statue &s;et up in the <HI>Palae&s;tra,</HI> with the names of tho&s;e that then were Governours of the Schools each month. On the other &s;ide, are the names of &s;everal Officers, under the Title of
&Pgr;&Agr;&Igr;&Dgr;&Egr;&Ugr;&Tgr;&Agr;&Igr;.
To illu&s;trate all which, would de&s;erve a particular di&s;|cour&s;e by it &s;elf; which at pre&s;ent I &s;hall forbear, le&s;t I &s;hould grow too voluminous. We &s;aw many more at other private hou&s;es, as at <HI>Kyra Irini, Georgadi Livaditis</HI> and <HI>Jani Mi&s;trigo;</HI> e&s;pecially one I cannot omit, being of <HI>Bernice,</HI> Daughter to King <HI>Agrippa.</HI></P>
<Q>&EEgr; &Bgr;&Ogr;&Ugr;&Lgr;&EEgr; &Egr;&Xgr; &Agr;&Rgr;&Egr;&Igr;&Ogr;&Pgr;&Agr;&Ggr;&Ogr;&Ugr; &Kgr;&Agr;&Igr;<LB>
&EEgr; &Bgr;&Ogr;&Ugr;&Lgr;&EEgr; &Tgr;&OHgr;&Ngr; &KHgr; &Kgr;&Agr;&Igr; &Ogr; &Dgr;&EEgr;&Mgr;&Ogr;&Sgr;&Igr;&Ogr;&Ugr;<LB>
&Lgr;&Igr;&Agr;&Ngr; &Bgr;&Egr;&Rgr;&Ngr;&Egr;&Igr;&Kgr;&EEgr;&Ngr; &Bgr;&Agr;&Sgr;&Igr;&Lgr;&Igr;&Sgr;&Sgr;&Agr;&Ngr;<LB>
&Mgr;&Egr;&Ggr;&Agr;&Lgr;&EEgr;&Ngr; &Igr;&Ogr;&Ugr;&Lgr;&Igr;&Ogr;&Ugr; &Agr;&Ggr;&Rgr;&Igr;&Pgr;&Pgr;&Agr; &Bgr;&Agr;&Sgr;&Igr;<LB>
&Lgr;&Egr;&OHgr;&Sgr; &Egr;&Kgr;&Ggr;&Ogr;&Ngr;&Ogr;&Ngr; &Dgr;&Igr;&Agr; &Tgr;&EEgr;&Sgr; &Pgr;&Rgr;&Ogr;&Ngr;&Ogr;&Igr;<LB>
&Agr;&Sgr; &Tgr;&Ogr;&Ugr; &Egr;&Pgr;&Igr; &Mgr;&Egr;&Lgr;&EEgr;&Tgr;&Ogr;&Ugr; &Tgr;&EEgr;&Sgr; &Pgr;&Ogr;&Lgr;&Egr;<LB>
&OHgr;&Sgr; &Tgr;&Igr;&Bgr;. &Kgr;&Lgr;&Agr;&Ugr;&Dgr;&Igr;&Ogr;&Ugr; &THgr;&Egr;&Ogr;&Ggr;&Egr;&Ngr;&Ogr;&Ugr;&Sgr;<LB></Q>
<P>That is, <HI>The Senate of the Areopagites, and the Senate con&s;i&s;ting of a Thou&s;and, and the Commons erected this Monument to Julia Bernice, the great Queen, Niece to King Julius Agrip|pa, for her Favour to them, when Tiberius Claudius Theogenes governed the City.</HI></P>
<P>This is &s;upppo&s;ed to be the &s;ame Queen <HI>Bernice,</HI> that is &s;poken of in the <HI>Acts of the Apo&s;tles.</HI></P>
<P>We &s;aw and copied many others very curious, lying about in Churches, in the Streets, and among the Walls of the Buildings, too numerous
<PB N="405" REF="170">here to give an account of. Tho&s;e few Marbles I had then, and &s;ince, collected, I have pre&s;ented to the Univer&s;ity of <HI>Oxon;</HI> where they have the honour to be placed among the famous <HI>Marmora Arundeliana &amp; Seldeniana.</HI></P>
<P>Only &s;ome few Figures and <HI>Ba&s;&s;o-relievo's</HI> I yet re&s;erve by me, of which the&s;e following are the mo&s;t con&s;iderable.</P>
<P><FIGURE>
<FIGDESC>statue of Demeter</FIGDESC>
<HEAD><HI>Lib:</HI> V.
&Dgr;&EEgr;&Mgr;&EEgr;&Tgr;&EEgr;&Rgr; &Slungr;&Egr;R&Egr;S</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<P>The fir&s;t is an Image of <HI>Ceres,</HI><NOTE PLACE="marg">CERES.</NOTE> a Godde&s;s much honoured by the <HI>A|thenians,</HI> by the name of <GAP DESC="foreign">; and of who&s;e my&s;teries, celebrated at her famous Temple at <HI>Eleu&s;is,</HI> mention is often made both by pro|phane and Divine Authours: e&s;pecially the Chri&s;tian Apologi&s;ts, who often &s;peak of them with great dete&s;tation. She is here repre&s;ented &s;it|ting, with a Basket on her Head, cloathed with a long Garment girded together ju&s;t below the Paps, holding a Lyon in her Lap, and a &s;acrifi|ting, with a Basket on her Head, cloathed with a long Garment girded together ju&s;t below the Paps, holding a Lyon in her Lap, and a &s;acrifi|cing Plate in one hand, and &s;omething that is round in the other. I have another fragment of the &s;ame Godde&s;s, only the Lyon is painted by her, and her left hand is &s;hut together, with a hole bored through, to hold, as I think, Ears of Corn. This I &s;uppo&s;e was a Dome&s;tick Image, u&s;ed at their private &s;uper&s;tition.</P>
<PB N="406" REF="171">
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<P>I have three <HI>Ba&s;&s;o-relievo's,</HI> repre&s;enting <HI>I&s;is</HI> and <HI>Serapis</HI> &s;itting on a Couch.<NOTE PLACE="marg">ISIS <HI>and</HI> SERAPIS.</NOTE> <HI>I&s;is</HI> is clothed with a long Ve&s;t, girded together below her Paps, and a loo&s;e Mantle about her Shoulders; She reacheth her right hand down, as receiving &s;omething; and in her left She holds a &s;quare Box with the Lid open. <HI>Serapis</HI> &s;its half naked, holding a <HI>Cor|nucopia</HI> in his right hand, and a Plate in his left, with his head covered with a kind of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> higher than his head. Before them &s;tands a Table to receive the Offerings, on which are things of divers Figures, round three &s;quare, and h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">lf round. Upon one of the <HI>Ba&s;&s;o-relievoe's</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">re is a Bag, which &s;eems to be a Bag of Money; whereof <HI>I&s;is</HI> takes out <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o put in he<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> Box, On the right hand of two of them, are a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">, and a Woman, and Children; I &s;uppo&s;e, coming to wor&s;hip, or to &s;acrifice. For on this <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> give you the Figure, there is a little Boy with a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">re&s;ent in his Hand, and a Bea&s;t by him, I take to be a Hog; but it is &s;ome what defaced. On this al&s;o is a Hor&s;es-head, as hung up<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> a Corner of the Room; but not on the re&s;t. <HI>I&s;ts</HI> and <HI>Serapis</HI> are repre&s;e<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ed in all three much alike: Only in one of them, <HI>I&s;is</HI> holds no Box; but collects her Money in her Lap: But in the other Figures they all differ. This &s;eems to be a Man, and his Wife, and three Children; being two Sons, and a Daughter. The &s;econd hath a Man, and his Wife, and three Sons. The third, a Man, and one Son. Whence I judge them to be Memorials of the Payments of Vows, made to tho&s;e Idols in times of Sickne&s;s or Di&s;tre&s;s: Such as the <HI>Ro|man</HI> Church u&s;ually now make, and pay to the Saints, and hang up in their Churches.</P>
<PB N="407" REF="171">
<P>Some others I have al&s;o; of which I am not yet well informed what they are: Of which, &s;ome other time, I may give an Account, toge|ther with tho&s;e many In&s;criptions I have, in a Treati&s;e by them&s;elves, if I find it worthy my pains. But this &s;hall now &s;uffice for our Ac|count of <HI>ATHENS.</HI></P>
<TRAILER>The End of the Fifth Book.</TRAILER>
